<paragraph blockId="18.[168,775,1087,1765]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1021">
Therophytes, native with wide distribution in the American continent; previously recorded from 
<collectingRegion country="Argentina" name="Buenos Aires" pageId="18" pageNumber="1021">Buenos Aires province</collectingRegion>
but not from mountainous areas.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[168,775,1087,1765]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1021">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[206,386,1336,1360]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1021">Characteristics.</emphasis>
Annual twining herb, to 
<quantity box="[659,727,1336,1360]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="18" pageNumber="1021" unit="cm" value="50.0">50 cm</quantity>
tall. A glabrous plant with short-winged stems. Leaves pinnately compond, with 2 linear leaflets and a terminal tendril, split into 1–3 segments; petiole 
<quantity box="[594,714,1438,1462]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="0.5" pageId="18" pageNumber="1021" unit="cm" value="1.0" valueMax="1.5" valueMin="0.5">0.5–1.5 cm</quantity>
long, stipules sagittate. Inflorescence: racemes, with 1–3 flow- ers, with glabrous sepals and white to blue petals. Fruit: a linear and erect legume, turning brown at maturity.
</paragraph>
