<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="1021" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="18.[168,775,1087,1765]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1021">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[206,336,1573,1597]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1021">Comments.</emphasis>
This is an infrequent species in the study area. It grows in intermediate to full sunlight on slopes with moderately deep, moist soils. 
<taxonomicName box="[545,730,1640,1664]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Lathyrus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="18" pageNumber="1021" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pusillus">
<emphasis box="[545,730,1640,1664]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="1021">Lathyrus pusillus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be recognized from the many other 
<taxonomicName box="[564,745,1674,1698]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Lathyrus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="18" pageNumber="1021" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[564,659,1674,1698]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="1021">Lathyrus</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
in the region by the presence of sagittate stipules and brown legumes that do not turn black when dry.
</paragraph>
